evidence: The microstructure and the mechanical behavior of equimolar Ti 20 Hf 20 Zr 20 Ta 20 Nb 20 high-entropy alloy in a wide range of initial strain rates between 10 -3 s -1 and 3.4  10 3 s -1 were studied. A significant increment in the yield strength with increasing strain rate was observed. The yield strength at 3.4  10 3 s -1 was about 40% higher than that measured at 10 -3 s -1.

The material exhibits a random crystallographic texture and the grain size values are in the range of 10 -350 µm with an average value of ~200 µm. For the specimen deformed at a velocity of 10.34 m s -1 the hardness was determined after the impact test which state corresponds to a plastic strain of 0.49 and a strain rate of 4700 s -1 . The flow stress calculated from the hardness was 1228 MPa.

In the pioneering work by Senkov et al. [15] such features were identified as a mixture of distorted shear bands and twins. The authors estimated the threshold stress for twinning somewhere above 600 MPa in TiHfZrTaNb equimolar HEA, which was deformed by compression at room temperature in the quasi-static regime.

Conclusions The effect of strain rate on the plastic behavior in equimolar Ti20Hf20Zr20Ta20Nb20 highentropy alloy was studied in the range of 10-3 s-1 -3.4  10 3 s-1. The difference in the mechanical performance at various strain rates was explained with the help of postmortem microstructure investigations using EBSD and XRD.
